v:4 c:$ m:T06-adsr-envelopes role:dev x:glicol/synthesis
gate: LOCKED

task: Give notes an amplitude envelope so they sound musical instead of clicky raw oscillators

requires: [FRONTEND_DEV]
out:
  - daww3/experiments/jam-sandbox/src/glicol-engine.ts

context: |
  INSTRUMENTS (glicol-engine.ts:20-33) are bare oscillator chains, e.g.
    saw_pad: (f) => `saw ${f} >> lpf 1200.0 1.0 >> mul 0.15`
  Notes hard on/off via rebuildGraph adding/removing the voice → instant
  amplitude steps → audible clicks on every note edge. A short attack/release
  envelope removes the clicks and is the single biggest perceived-quality win.

  Glicol supports envelope nodes (e.g. an envelope/EnvPerc-style or an
  amplitude ramp via `mul` with an env signal — verify exact 0.4 syntax in
  node_modules/glicol). Apply a short attack (~5-15ms) and release (~80-200ms)
  per voice.

steps:
  1. Confirm the envelope primitive available in installed Glicol 0.4.
  2. Wrap each instrument voice with a short AR envelope so onset/offset ramp
     instead of stepping. Keep per-instrument character (don't homogenize).
  3. Because rebuildGraph drops a voice on note-off, ensure release is handled —
     either via an envelope that completes before removal, or a brief lingering
     voice on noteOff. Keep it simple; avoid a full voice-allocator rewrite.
  4. Re-check CPU: envelopes shouldn't meaningfully worsen the S03 graph cost.

caution: |
  Stuck/hung notes are the failure mode. Verify every noteOn has a matching
  silence after noteOff (no infinite sustain). One objective: envelopes only —
  no new instruments, no filter modulation.

done:
  - Notes fade in/out (no click on press/release), audibly smoother
  - No stuck notes; noteOff still silences within the release window
  - Each instrument keeps its distinct timbre
  - tsc --noEmit passes
